The paper deals with the fundamental problem of propositional satisfiability (SAT) and its worst-case hardness, which falls under the category of computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The study of random structures and their analysis is a common theme in discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also discusses the use of rigorous and non-rigorous techniques, which could fall under information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the study of real-world instances and their modeling could be relevant to social and information networks (cs.SI).
